The consortium’s project will have an initial cost of $2 billion, with an aim to start production by 2022, an ANGP spokesperson said on the sidelines of the Africa Oil Week conference in Cape Town. Italy’s Eni will operate the project, and the members will share costs according to participation. Chevron will take a 31% stake, Eni 25.6%, Sonangol P&P 19.8%, Total 11.8% and BP 11.8%. The Soyo LNG plant is designed to process 1.1 billion cubic feet of natural gas per day and has the capacity to produce 5.2 million tons of LNG per year, as well as natural gas, propane, butane and condensate. --Reuters--